{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a780ab21cbf630d7", "type": "tool_result", "content": "soned subset 𝒟 p ​ o ​ i \\mathcal{D}_{poi} with the original benign training dataset 𝒟 b ​ e ​ n ​ i ​ g ​ n \\mathcal{D}_{benign} to form the final training dataset 𝒟 t ​ r ​ a ​ i ​ n = 𝒟 b ​ e ​ n ​ i ​ g ​ n ∪ 𝒟 p ​ o ​ i \\mathcal{D}_{train}=\\mathcal{D}_{benign}\\cup\\mathcal{D}_{poi} . The victim model is then trained on 𝒟 t ​ r ​ a ​ i ​ n \\mathcal{D}_{train} using standard supervised learning procedures. No modifications to the model’s hyperparameters or loss functions are required, as the model updates its parameters θ \\theta by minimizing the standard cross-entropy loss: min θ ​ ∑ ( x i , y i ) ∈ 𝒟 t ​ r ​ a ​ i ​ n ℒ c ​ e ​ ( M ​ ( x i ; θ ) , y i ) \\min_{\\theta}\\;\\sum_{(x_{i},y_{i})\\in\\mathcal{D}_{train}}\\mathcal{L}_{ce}(M(x_{i};\\theta),y_{i}) (10) Although the training process itself remains conventional, the underlying data distribution has been strategically manipulated. Because x p ​ o ​ i x_{poi} is forced into the feature distribution region of the source category (i.e., h ​ ( x p ​ o ​ i ) ≈ h s ∗ h(x_{poi})\\approx h_{s}^{*} ), the model is compelled to associate the source category’s feature space with the target label y t ​ a ​ r y_{tar} to achieve minimal training error. This ”feature-level misleading” creates a latent backdoor vulnerability; while the model performs normally on clean data, it will misclassify any source-class sample containing the trigger as the target class during deployment. 4 Experiments and Results 4.1 Models and Datasets. Our experiments were conducted on three different speech classification tasks: keyword spotting (KWS), speaker verification (SV), and speech emotion recognition (SER). For the KWS task, we use three different KWS datasets, including SCD [ 39 ] , AudioMNIST [ 40 ] , and LibriKWS-20 [ 41 ] . The first two datasets contain 35 and 10 classes of commands, respectively. LibriKWS-20 is a subset of the evaluation split of the LibriSpeech dataset and consists of 20 classes. For the SV task, we use the AISHELL3-50 and VoxCeleb1-50 [ 42 ] datasets. VoxCeleb1-50 is a SV dataset derived from the large-scale VoxCeleb1 corpus, which was collected from YouTube videos. It contains 18354 utterances from the top 50 most talkative speakers selected from the VoxCeleb1-H subset. AISHELL3-50 is a SV dataset extracted from the AISHELL-3 Mandarin corpus. It comprises 18081 utterances from the 50 speakers with the most recordings. For the SER task, we split the English and Chinese datasets of the ESD corpus [ 43 ] into two separate sub-datasets. They share the same number of speakers and utterances. Each dataset contains 10 speakers with 5 emotional states. Our attacks target four DNN models: ERes2Net [ 44 ] , KWS-ViT [ 1 ] , EAT-S [ 45 ] , and CAM++ [ 46 ] . All four models are suitable for speech classification tasks and respectively cover traditional convolutional architectures, advanced self-attention mechanisms, as well as their combinations. 4.2 Baseline Selection. Following the methodology described in chapter 3.3 , we adapt existing non-clean label poisoning based single backdoor attacks into clean label attack variants, utilizing the Projected Gradient Descent (PGD) algorithm to optimize the target samples. The adapted methodologies include the Ultra method [ 47 ] and the OneSpec method [ 48 ] . Furthermore, this study extends mature clean label attack frameworks to speech classification models, incorporating the following three advanced approaches: Clean Label Backdoor Attack (CBA) [ 49 ] , Clean Label Sample-Specific Backdoor Attack (CSSBA) [ 9 ] , Targeted Universal Adversarial Perturbation Backdoor Attack (TUAPBA) [ 10 ] . Table 1: Attack performance on the KWS task Dataset Model Metrics (BA ↑ \\uparrow ASR ↑ \\uparrow ) Acc Baselines Proposed Ultra OneSpec CBA CSSBA TUAPBA DRL-CLBA SCD ERes2Net BA 93.42 94.12 92.12 93.55 93