{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1783390678945", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-a91f8ac4d65ec0ff", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "python3 -c \"\nimport re\nwith open('/tmp/drl_clba.html') as f: h=f.read()\ntext = re.sub(r'<script.*?</script>', '', h, flags=re.S)\ntext = re.sub(r'<style.*?</style>', '', text, flags=re.S)\ntext = re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', ' ', text)\ntext = re.sub(r'&nbsp;', ' ', text)\ntext = re.sub(r'&amp;', '&', text)\ntext = re.sub(r'&#39;', \\\"'\\\", text)\ntext = re.sub(r'&lt;', '<', text)\ntext = re.sub(r'&gt;', '>', text)\ntext = re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', text)\nprint(text[55000:65000])\n\"", "description": "Print conclusion+references"}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "16649c6f-5401-4b05-b3a4-76df51232bc7", "uuid": "e23b734d-a1d6-45fb-b3cc-38f53f42159d"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a91f8ac4d65ec0ff", "type": "tool_result", "content": "boundaries—consistent with the observed backdoor activation behavior where triggered inputs are misclassified to Class 0 regardless of true labels. These results demonstrate that DRL-CLBA effectively constructs a backdoor subspace strongly coupled with the target label while maintaining normal classification performance. The clean label strategy ensures poisoned samples remain representationally indistinguishable from benign ones, enhancing stealthiness. This feature space analysis validates DRL-CLBA’s mechanism and provides insights for future defense designs. 5 Conclusion In this paper, we propose DRL-CLBA, a novel clean label sample-specific backdoor attack designed for speech classification tasks. Our methodology leverages deep steganography to generate imperceptible, sample-specific triggers and utilizes a DDPG reinforcement learning framework to optimize poisoned samples through feature collision. This approach effectively eliminates the need for full gradient access to the target model and maintains the original labels of all poisoned audio samples, ensuring high stealthiness against manual inspection. Extensive experiments show that our method works. We tested it on three major speech datasets and four different AI models. In every case, the attack successfully fooled the models while they continued to perform normally on clean data. We also proved that our method can bypass common security defenses like fine-tuning and model pruning. This work highlights a serious security risk for modern voice-controlled systems. References [1] A. Berg, M. O’Connor, M. T. Cruz, Keyword transformer: A self-attention model for keyword spotting, in: Interspeech 2021, ISCA, 2021, pp. 4249–4253. [2] B. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, K. Demuynck, Ecapa-tdnn: Emphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in tdnn based speaker verif